      <tax:div type="materials_examined" obkms_id="f324cc64-89c3-4ddb-93f5-576a58c9f3b3" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:p>Material examined.Type material:Holotype3: ‘Arabia: Khafs.26.ii.1935. H. St. J. B. Philby, B. M.1935 –222 ’, ‘Type’, ‘<tax:name obkms_id="03aa94f1-526d-40be-b08f-ba0858c3ce97" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Prout</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>Lithostege inanis Prout</tax:name>Holotype3 ’; allotype Ƥ: same data; coll.BMNH.</tax:p>
        <tax:p>Additional material:1 Ƥ:Iran, Belutschistan, Iranshahr,800 m,1.-10.III.1954, [leg.] Richter u. Schäuffele, gen. prep.1012 /2010 H. R. Preparations of genitalia:13,2 Ƥ.</tax:p>
      </tax:div>
      <tax:div type="description">
        <tax:p>Description &amp; Diagnosis. Wingspan of the single specimen fromIran:22 mm. Wings similar to<tax:name obkms_id="3bac0646-6de3-49f4-9f27-9e4cfab246f3" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>L. fissurata</tax:name>, but without apical dark grey line on forewing (Fig.18). Female genitalia (Fig.68) with very short apophyses anteriores (0.1 of apophyses posteriores) and a short funnel-shaped antrum; the pear-shaped corpus bursae fully spinulate, with a small anterior diverticulum. Female genitalia of<tax:name obkms_id="908a659b-01f4-44ac-85c6-44a470567e6f" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>fissurata</tax:name> without distinct differences. Also the male genitalia of theholotype (studied) almost identical.</tax:p>
      </tax:div>
      <tax:div type="materials_examined" obkms_id="f5d889f3-3005-47d2-9637-d90461e0954e" obkms_process="TRUE">
        <tax:p>Taxonomic note.Wiltshire (1990) synonymised<tax:name obkms_id="d674eb02-1df8-4684-93a9-ccedc578123f" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fitzgeraldi</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>L. fitzgeraldi</tax:name>Wiltshire,1947 with<tax:name obkms_id="302ad74d-3353-497f-9966-384a3d05b1be" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Prout, 1941</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>L. inanis Prout,1941</tax:name> and simultaneously downgraded this taxon to a subspecies of<tax:name obkms_id="39103eee-dedc-4f66-a035-b2edf34d7f87" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Mabille, 1888</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>L. fissurataMabille,1888</tax:name>. The single examined specimen fromIran was recorded byHausmann &amp; Seguna (2005) as<tax:name obkms_id="c269c19d-2266-42bb-a902-47f8fe7b1573" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:Subspecies>inanis</dwc:Subspecies><dwc:taxonRank>subspecies</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Prout, 1941</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>L. fissurata inanis Prout,1941</tax:name>. The female genitalia of this specimen are highly similar to those of<tax:name obkms_id="03e284d2-1b3e-4e85-bf71-f6860d5c1662" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>L. fissurata</tax:name> (figured inHausmann &amp; Seguna (2005)). Also the male genitalia of theholotype of<tax:name obkms_id="ecd3a416-4fc1-4d87-9958-2958dc348200" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Prout</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>L. inanis Prout</tax:name> fit well with those of<tax:name obkms_id="34dfa0d0-29f2-44a6-af93-f9b00dd7d818" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank><dwc:scientificNameAuthorship>Mabille. On</dwc:scientificNameAuthorship></tax:xmldata>L. fissurata Mabille. On</tax:name> the other hand, a separation on species-level of<tax:name obkms_id="aeb7bdc8-6e34-4cb6-838e-32edd642b623" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>inanis</tax:name> and<tax:name obkms_id="d55ad89e-fe3c-48c9-9772-e31e04c25726" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>fissurata</tax:name> is supported by genetic differentiation between these two taxa. DNAbarcoding of5 specimens of<tax:name obkms_id="62a3a1da-aadf-4662-b1c8-f8dd167eeb02" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>fissurata</tax:name> from a wide area of distribution (Mauretania:2;Tunisia:2;Israel:1) does not show any intraspecific variation, but comparing these with three barcodes of<tax:name obkms_id="5a88593f-40f5-48d1-aca4-6737587a2456" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>inanis</tax:name> (fromUnited Arab Emirates) reveals a distance of 2.35%, suggesting<tax:name obkms_id="83a604ae-cabe-4f9d-b3ae-923197d6ac9c" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>inanis</tax:name> to be a distinct species. Conventionally, a barcode difference exceeding2 % is understood as an argument of a species-level difference. It seems not unlikely that long-term isolation between Iranian and Arab populations led to a cryptic species (“in statu nascendi”) inIran, but without further studies of more material we are not able to decide this question. So here we followHausmann &amp; Seguna (2005), regarding<tax:name obkms_id="e19a9d94-a2fa-4bec-8c87-3f5ff63c8b1f" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>inanis</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>inanis</tax:name> as a subspecies of<tax:name obkms_id="ee9db932-978b-4aa4-9810-6683e2ebb6fd" obkms_process="TRUE"><tax:xmldata><dwc:Kingdom>Animalia</dwc:Kingdom><dwc:Class>Insecta</dwc:Class><dwc:Order>Lepidoptera</dwc:Order><dwc:Family>Geometridae</dwc:Family><dwc:Genus>Lithostege</dwc:Genus><dwc:Species>fissurata</dwc:Species><dwc:taxonRank>species</dwc:taxonRank></tax:xmldata>L. fissurata</tax:name>.</tax:p>
        <tax:p>Bionomics. Specimens studied are collected in January and February.</tax:p>
      </tax:div>
